IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: PROVIDE FOOD FOR HUNGRY PEOPLE WHILE STRIVING TO END HUNGER IN OUR COMMUNITY.
IRS990.MissionDesc: THE GREATER CHICAGO FOOD DEPOSITORY IS THE NONPROFIT FOOD BANK SERVING COOK COUNTY. OUR MISSION - IS TO END HUNGER. WE BELIEVE FOOD IS A BASIC HUMAN RIGHT. TO ACHIEVE OUR MISSION, WE WORK IN PARTNERSHIP WITH A NETWORK OF COMMUNITY-BASED ORGANIZATIONS AND INDIVIDUALS. TOGETHER, WE CONNECT OUR NEIGHBORS WITH HEALTHY FOOD, LIFT OUR VOICES AND ADVANCE SOLUTIONS THAT ADDRESS THE ROOT CAUSES OF HUNGER POVERTY, SYSTEMIC INEQUITY AND STRUCTURAL RACISM. TOGETHER, WE ARE GREATER. TOGETHER, WE CAN END HUNGER.
IRS990.Desc: THE GREATER CHICAGO FOOD DEPOSITORY PROVIDES EMERGENCY FOOD ASSISTANCE IN COOK COUNTY, ILLINOIS BY DISTRIBUTING FOOD GRANTS THROUGH A NETWORK OF MORE THAN 700 FOOD PANTRIES, SOUP KITCHENS, SHELTERS AND PROGRAMS. THE FOOD DISTRIBUTED IS DONATED, PURCHASED OR RECEIVED FROM FEDERAL PROGRAMS.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: THE GREATER CHICAGO FOOD DEPOSITORY PROVIDES PROGRAMS TO ALLEVIATE HUNGER AMONG PRIORITY POPULATIONS INCLUDING CHILDREN, STUDENTS, OLDER ADULTS AND VETERANS. THE ORGANIZATION ALSO OFFERS WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT FOR UNEMPLOYED AND UNDEREMPLOYED INDIVIDUALS. OTHER PROGRAMS INCLUDE AFTER-SCHOOL AND SUMMER MEALS FOR CHILDREN, FOOD DISTRIBUTIONS FOR OLDER ADULTS, FOOD DISTRIBUTIONS AT SCHOOLS, AND FEDERAL BENEFITS OUTREACH.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: MOBILE RESPONSES REACH POPULATIONS THAT OFTEN DON'T HAVE ACCESS TO TRADITIONAL EMERGENCY ASSISTANCE PROGRAMS. THE FOOD DEPOSITORY'S PRODUCE MOBILE DISTRIBUTES FRESH FRUIT AND VEGETABLES IN HIGH-NEED COMMUNITIES, WHILE THE MOBILE PANTRY PROVIDES PRODUCE, PROTEIN AND SHELF-STABLE GROCERIES TO HUNGRY INDIVIDUALS ON EVENINGS AND WEEKENDS. THE FRESH TRUCK OFFERS PRODUCE TO FOOD INSECURE PATIENTS OF HEALTH CLINICS THROUGHOUT COOK COUNTY.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION'S ADVOCACY AGENDA SUPPORTS HUNGER RELIEF EFFORTS ANNUALLY IN SPRINGFIELD AND WASHINGTON D.C. STAFF MEET WITH AND SEND LETTERS AND OTHER INFORMATION TO ELECTED OFFICIALS, THEIR STAFFS, AND/OR GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS REGARDING PENDING LEGISLATION AND ADMINISTRATIVE ISSUES RELATED TO HUNGER RELIEF PROGRAMS OR OTHER ANTI-POVERTY ISSUES. WE ALSO PERIODICALLY PUBLISH REPORTS AND SUMMARIES ON THESE KEY ISSUES THAT ARE MADE AVAILABLE TO ELECTED AND GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS AND THE GENERAL PUBLIC. THE ORGANIZATION ALSO WORKS TO INFORM AND MOBILIZE GRASSROOTS VOLUNTEERS ON IMPORTANT PUBLIC POLICY ISSUES.

THE OBJECTIVES OF THE FOUNDERS' FUND AND THE BOARD-DESIGNATED FREEDOM FROM HUNGER FUND ENDOWMENTS ARE (1) TO PROVIDE A POOL OF CAPITAL SUFFICIENT TO FUND THE OPERATING RESERVE; (2) TO PROVIDE A SOURCE OF FUNDS FOR TARGETED CAPITAL PROJECTS, PROGRAMMATIC GROWTH, AND OTHER USES AS DEEMED APPROPRIATE BY THE FOOD DEPOSITORY'S BOARD OF DIRECTORS (THE "BOARD"), CONSISTENT WITH THE FOOD DEPOSITORY'S STRATEGIC PLAN; AND (3) TO PROVIDE AN IDENTIFIED PORTION OF THE FUND TO THE ANNUAL OPERATING BUDGET OF THE FOOD DEPOSITORY TO PAY OPERATING EXPENSES. THE FIRST TWO OBJECTIVES ARE FOR LONG-TERM INVESTMENT GOALS, WHILE THE THIRD OBJECTIVE MEETS SHORT-TERM INVESTMENT AND LIQUIDITY NEEDS.

THE FOOD DEPOSITORY IS A NOT-FOR-PROFIT CORPORATION AND IS EXEMPT FROM TAX UNDER THE PROVISIONS OF INTERNAL REVENUE CODE SECTION 501(C)(3). ACCOUNTING PRINCIPLES GENERALLY ACCEPTED IN THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA REQUIRE MANAGEMENT TO EVALUATE TAX POSITIONS TAKEN BY THE FOOD DEPOSITORY AND RECOGNIZE A TAX LIABILITY IF THE FOOD DEPOSITORY HAS TAKEN AN UNCERTAIN POSITION THAT MORE LIKELY THAN NOT WOULD NOT BE SUSTAINED UPON EXAMINATION BY THE IRS OR OTHER APPLICABLE TAXING AUTHORITIES. MANAGEMENT HAS ANALYZED THE TAX POSITIONS TAKEN BY THE FOOD DEPOSITORY AND HAS CONCLUDED THAT, AS OF JUNE 30, 2022 AND 2021, THERE ARE NO UNCERTAIN POSITIONS TAKEN OR EXPECTED TO BE TAKEN THAT WOULD REQUIRE RECOGNITION OF A LIABILITY OR DISCLOSURE IN THE FINANCIAL STATEMENTS. THE FOOD DEPOSITORY IS SUBJECT TO ROUTINE AUDITS BY TAXING JURISDICTIONS; HOWEVER, THERE ARE CURRENTLY NO AUDITS FOR ANY TAX PERIODS IN PROGRESS.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 15
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: IN 2020 THE GREATER CHICAGO FOOD DEPOSITORY ENGAGED A 3RD PARTY COMPENSATION CONSULTING FIRM, COMMONWEALTH HR CONSULTING (CHRC) TO CONDUCT MARKETING PRICING FOR ALL POSITIONS IN THE ORGANIZATION EXCLUDING THE VICE PRESIDENT AND CHIEF POSITIONS. THE EXECUTIVE POSITIONS WERE REVIEWED BY COMMONWEALTH HR IN AUGUST OF 2021. CHRC CREATED AN UPDATED GRADE AND RANGE STRUCTURE, PLACED INCUMBENTS INTO NEW STRUCTURE, IDENTIFIED INCUMBENTS WHO MAY BE OUTSIDE RANGE OF THE NEW STRUCTURE. CHRC CONDUCTED MARKET PRICING USING THE FOLLOWING SURVEY SOURCES: - ECONOMIC RESEARCH INSTITUTE, INC. ("ERI") - COMPANALYST MARKET DATA (PROFESSIONAL VERSION OF SALARY.COM) - FEEDING AMERICA COMPENSATION 2020 SURVEY - PAYSCALE AND 2019 NON-PROFIT TIMES SURVEY (AS NEEDED) CHRC USED THE FOLLOWING SCOPES FOR GCFD: - "NONPROFIT" INDUSTRIES AND/OR "ALL INDUSTRIES", BASED ON SPECIFIC POSITION ROLES - HIGHER ED, HEALTH CARE, AND ARTS & CULTURE (DEVELOPMENT) - CHICAGO AREA - REVENUE - $100 MILLION/200 FULL-TIME EMPLOYEES STAFF COMPENSATION IS REVIEWED AND APPROVED ANNUALLY BY THE CHIEF EXECUTIVE OFFICER (CEO), CHIEF OPERATION OFFICER AND VICE PRESIDENT OF PEOPLE & CULTURE. CEO COMPENSATION IS REVIEWED AND APPROVED BY THE BOARD COMPENSATION COMMITTEE WITH FINAL APPROVAL BY THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE OF THE BOARD.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: PUBLIC DISCLOSURE OF DOCUMENTS - GOVERNING DOCUMENTS AND FINANCIAL STATEMENTS ARE AVAILABLE THROUGH APPLICABLE GOVERNMENTAL AGENCIES; THE CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY IS AVAILABLE UPON WRITTEN REQUEST OF THE ORGANIZATION.

IN 2018, THE FOOD DEPOSITORY LAUNCHED THE NOURISH CAPITAL CAMPAIGN. THE CAMPAIGN SEEKS TO RAISE APPROXIMATELY $75 MILLION TO SUPPORT CAPITAL IMPROVEMENTS TO THE EXISTING FOOD DEPOSITORY FACILITY AND EXPANSION OF THE FACILITY TO EXPAND PROGRAMMATIC CAPABILITIES.
THE PROCESS HAS NOT CHANGED FROM THE PRIOR YEAR.
